  "transcript": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, the mango season is here, what's your go-to recipe?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Aamras is my favorite — just ripe mangoes, a splash of milk, and a touch of sugar. Sometimes I add cardamom, it's sooo soothing after exams. Have you tried it?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Aamras sounds lovely — I get that post-exam craving for something sweet. What’s your secret for the smooth texture?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Blend it long! I use a hand blender, go slow with 1-2 cups at a time. If it's grainy, add more milk, chai, or even yogurt. Sometimes I \"dabba\" it — press through a sieve, but that's tedious. You?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Blend it long\" is a good tip — you’re doing great, just a tiny tweak: we say \"using a hand blender\". What’s your go-to fruit for summer?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Watermelon is my summer savior — juicy and refreshing. I usually cut it into cubes or make a sherbet. Sometimes I add a bit of salt and mint leaves, it's a quick cool-down after long study sessions. What about you?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Watermelon with mint and salt is a hit — you’re doing great, just a tiny tweak: we say \"I usually cut it into cubes or make a sherbet\". What’s your favourite way to enjoy mangoes?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I love mango lassi on hot days — blend mango, yogurt, a bit of sugar, and ice. Sometimes I add \"elaichi\" for flavor. It’s quick and gives me energy during study breaks. Do you have a mango recipe you like?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Mango lassi sounds perfect for study breaks, you’re doing great, just a tiny tweak: we say \"I love mango lassi on hot days\". What’s the first thing you look for when buying a mango?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I check the color and smell — a good mango should be fragrant and have a nice golden hue. The skin should be smooth, and it should feel heavy for its size. Oh, and a little dent when pressed is a good sign! What do you look for?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Color, smell, and a little dent — that’s a smart way to pick mangoes. What part of the mango do you prefer — the softer part near the stone or the juicier outer flesh?"
    }
  ],
